      <h3><a name="Tuesday, April 26, 2005" href="#Tuesday, April 26, 2005">
          <font color="#660000">Tuesday, April 26, 2005</font></a></h3>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="111456133742278524"></a>
    
    <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-08-31 -->
    <a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2005-7/0425m.html#item10"
                    title="external link">
    How Effective Is <em>Your</em> Software QA?
    </a>
    </font></h2>
    
    
    <p>
	<p><a href="http://www.acm.org/technews/articles/2005-7/0425m.html#item10">ACM News Service: Survey &ndash; Formal QA Process Key to Improve Testing Results</a>.&nbsp; This is a distillation of a research survey, and it is a little difficult to figure out how these things slice and dice.&nbsp; The bottom line is, &ldquo;More than half of the 129 execs who rigorously adhere to a formal QA discipline said such a strategy was very effective at winnowing out defects prior to implementation.&rdquo;&nbsp; To put this in some sort of perspective, &ldquo;about two-thirds of the 32 percent of respondents who saw massive gains in application quality consistently apply a formal QA plan.&rdquo;</p><p>Kathleen Ohlson&rsquo;s 2005-04-18 <a href="http://www.adtmag.com/article.asp?id=10960"><em>Application Development Trends</em> article</a> mixes in more of these weird statistics.</p><hr /><small>[dh:2005-04-27T01:14Z A quick update to provide a title and let you know what the article is about without having to read it first.]</small>
    </p>
	<span class="byline">posted by orcmid
       at <a href="http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2005/04/how-effective-is-your-software-qa.asp">4/26/2005 05:22:00 PM</a>,
